Instead of iterating over all possible integer numbers, let&#39;s iterate over all possible sequences&lt;br&gt;

    a1^n + a2^n + a3^n +  .. + an^n = A, where 0  ai  9

and checking corresponding sums A for &quot;Armstrongeness&quot;.

As sum is commutative (a+b = b+a) we need to iterate only over non-decreasing sequences:&lt;br&gt;

    a1^n  a2^n  a3^n   ..  an^n

For example, lets find all 3-digit Armstrong numbers:

    0^3 + 0^3 + 0^3 = 0
    0^3 + 0^3 + 1^3 = 1
    0^3 + 0^3 + 2^3 = 8
    ...
    0^3 + 3^3 + 6^3 = 243
    0^3 + 3^3 + 7^3 = 370 &lt;--  Armstrong number
    0^3 + 3^3 + 8^3 = 539
    ...
    0^3 + 4^3 + 6^3 = 280
    0^3 + 4^3 + 7^3 = 407 &lt;-- Armstrong number
    0^3 + 4^3 + 8^3 = 576
    ...
    1^3 + 3^3 + 4^3 = 92
    1^3 + 3^3 + 5^3 = 153 &lt;-- Armstrong number
    1^3 + 3^3 + 6^3 = 244
    1^3 + 3^3 + 7^3 = 371 &lt;-- Armstrong number
    1^3 + 3^3 + 8^3 = 540
    ...
    9^3 + 9^3 + 9^3 = 2187

There is 900 3-digit numbers, but only 178 possible 3-digit permutations. Does not sound like big deal, however for 900&#39;000&#39;000&#39;000&#39;000&#39;000 18-digit numbers, there is only 4&#39;515&#39;854 permutations.

Algorithm complexity is `10^N / N!`, still exponential, but drastically faster than initial  `10^N` solution.

My written on Java implementation computes all numbers by ~2 sec on my machine:

```java
package org.example;

import java.util.ArrayList;
import java.util.Arrays;
import java.util.List;

public class Main {
    private static int[] digits;
    private static long sumOfPows = 0;
    private static long[] pows;
    private static long min = 0;
    private static long max = 0;
    private static List&lt;Long&gt; result = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        for (int numOfDigits = 1; numOfDigits &lt;= 19 ; numOfDigits++) {
            search(numOfDigits);
        }

        System.out.println(result);
    }


    private static void search(int numOfDigits) {
        digits = new int[numOfDigits];
        sumOfPows = 0;
        pows = new long[10];
        min = powerN(10, numOfDigits-1);
        max = powerN(10, numOfDigits);
        if (max &lt; 0) { // check for overflow
            max = Long.MAX_VALUE;
        }
        for (int i = 0; i &lt; pows.length; i++) {
            pows[i] = powerN(i, numOfDigits);
        }
        searchRecursively(0);
    }


    private static void searchRecursively(int i) {
        if (i == digits.length) {
            // sequence fully constructed, lets test it for &quot;Armstrongeness&quot;
            if (min &lt;= sumOfPows &amp;&amp; sumOfPows &lt; max) { // check for right number of digits
                if (isArmstrong(digits, sumOfPows)) {
                    result.add(sumOfPows);
                }
            }
        } else {
            // we have a_1, a_2, a_(i-1) sequence, let&#39;s construct next a_i member
            // a_i should be in interval [a_(i-1)..9] or in interval [0..9] if i=0
            int minDigit = i &gt; 0 ? digits[i-1] : 0;
            for (int j = minDigit; j &lt;= 9; j++) {
                digits[i] = j;
                sumOfPows += pows[j];
                if (sumOfPows &gt;= 0 &amp;&amp; sumOfPows &lt; max) { // check for overflow
                    searchRecursively(i + 1);
                }
                sumOfPows -= pows[j]; // backtracking
            }
        }
    }

    private static boolean isArmstrong(int[] digits, long sumOfPows) {
        int[] digitsSorted = toDigits(sumOfPows, digits.length);
        return Arrays.equals(digits, digitsSorted);
    }

    private static int[] toDigits(long num, int len) {
        int[] result = new int[len];
        while(num &gt; 0) {
            result[--len] = (int)(num % 10);
            num /= 10;
        }
        Arrays.sort(result);
        return result;
    }

    private static long powerN(int number, int power){
        long res = 1;
        for (int i = 0; i &lt; power; i++) {
            res *= number;
        }
        return res;
    }
}
```

