# Write super-simple code

You are combining functions within a single line of code. Debugging your app is generally made easier if you restrict each line to a single operation. 

Also, super simple code happens to be easiest for a [JVM][1] to optimize at runtime.

Another benefit is that short sweet lines provide an opportunity to name results with an explanatory name. This makes your code more [self-documenting][2].

So notice in example code below how we accomplish one step at a time, one line at a time.

# Code point

Other Answers are correct. However, those Answers and your Question use the legacy type `char`. 

As a 16-bit value, `char` is physically incapable of representing most characters. The `char` type and its wrapper class `Character` have been essentially broken since Java 2, and legacy since Java 5. 

Instead, make a habit of using [code point][3] integer numbers. 

    String input = &quot;A&quot; ; 
    int codePoint = input.codePointAt( 0 );

Unicode is a superset of US-ASCII. So the first 128 code points (0-127) are indeed the ASCII codes you requested.  

Test if the input is a letter:

    if( Character.isLetter( codePoint ) ) {
         
    } else {  reject users input }

Test if the input is uppercase:

    if( Character.isUpperCase( codePoint ) ) {  } else {  reject users input } 

Convert the code point back to text. 

    String upper = Character.toString( codePoint ) ;

Get the lowercase partner for that uppercase letter.  

    int codePointOfLowercase = Character.toLowerCase( codePoint ) ;
    String lower = Character.toString( codePointOfLowercase ) ;


Be aware that not all languages have the notion of upper and lower case.

## Example code

Here is an entire example app.

```java
package work.basil.example.text;

import java.util.Scanner;

public class UpperLower
{
    public static void main ( String[] args )
    {
        Scanner scanner = new Scanner( System.in );

        System.out.println( &quot;Enter an uppercase letter A-Z, from basic English/Latin alphabet:&quot; );

        String input = scanner.nextLine();  // Read user input
        int codePoint = input.codePointAt( 0 );
        if ( Character.isLetter( codePoint ) )
        {
            if ( Character.isUpperCase( codePoint ) )
            {
                String upper = Character.toString( codePoint );
                int codePointOfLowercase = Character.toLowerCase( codePoint );
                String lower = Character.toString( codePointOfLowercase );
                System.out.println( &quot;You entered uppercase letter: &quot; + upper + &quot; which has a code point of: &quot; + codePoint + &quot;.&quot; );
                System.out.println( &quot;The matching lowercase character is: &quot; + lower + &quot;, code point: &quot; + codePointOfLowercase + &quot;.&quot; );
            }
            else
            {
                System.out.println( &quot;Oops, the letter you entered was not uppercase. Program ending. &quot; );
            }
        }
        else
        {
            System.out.println( &quot;Oops, you entered something other than a letter, such as a digit or punctuation. Program ending. &quot; );
        }
    }
}
